Books
| Books of The Times 
Making the iBio for Apple‚Äôs Genius

By JANET MASLINOCT. 21, 2011



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









After Steve Jobs anointed Walter Isaacson as his authorized biographer in 2009, he took Mr. Isaacson to see the Mountain View, Calif., house in which he had lived as a boy. He pointed out its ‚Äúclean design‚Äù and ‚Äúawesome little features.‚Äù He praised the developer, Joseph Eichler, who built more than 11,000 homes in California subdivisions, for making an affordable product on a mass-market scale. And he showed Mr. Isaacson the stockade fence built 50 years earlier by his father, Paul Jobs.‚ÄúHe loved doing things right,‚Äù Mr. Jobs said. ‚ÄúHe even cared about the look of the parts you couldn‚Äôt see.‚ÄùMr. Jobs, the brilliant and protean creator whose inventions so utterly transformed the allure of technology, turned those childhood lessons into an all-purpose theory of intelligent design. He gave Mr. Isaacson a chance to play by the same rules. His story calls for a book that is clear, elegant and concise enough to qualify as an iBio. Mr. Isaacson‚Äôs ‚ÄúSteve Jobs‚Äù does its solid best to hit that target.
Photo






Steve Jobs, leaving the stage after introducing the iPad, the latest in a long line of his inventions, in January 2010.

Credit
            Jim Wilson/The New York Times        


As a biographer of Albert Einstein and Benjamin Franklin, Mr. Isaacson knows how to explicate and celebrate genius: revered, long-dead genius. But he wrote ‚ÄúSteve Jobs‚Äù as its subject was mortally ill, and that is a more painful and delicate challenge. (He had access to members of the Jobs family at a difficult time.) Mr. Jobs promised not to look over Mr. Isaacson‚Äôs shoulder, and not to meddle with anything but the book‚Äôs cover. (Boy, does it look great.) And he expressed approval that the book would not be entirely flattering. But his legacy was at stake. And there were awkward questions to be asked. At the end of the volume, Mr. Jobs answers the question ‚ÄúWhat drove me?‚Äù by discussing himself in the past tense.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Isaacson treats ‚ÄúSteve Jobs‚Äù as the biography of record, which means that it is a strange book to read so soon after its subject‚Äôs death. Some of it is an essential Silicon Valley chronicle, compiling stories well known to tech aficionados but interesting to a broad audience. Some of it is already quaint. Mr. Jobs‚Äôs first job was at Atari, and it involved the game Pong. (‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre under 30, ask your parents,‚Äù Mr. Isaacson writes.) Some, like an account of the release of the iPad 2, is so recent that it is hard to appreciate yet, even if Mr. Isaacson says the device comes to life ‚Äúlike the face of a tickled baby.‚Äù¬† Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





And some is definitely intended for future generations. ‚ÄúIndeed,‚Äù Mr. Isaacson writes, ‚Äúits success came not just from the beauty of the hardware but from the applications, known as apps, that allowed you to indulge in all sorts of delightful activities.‚Äù One that he mentions, which will be as quaint as Pong some day, features the use of a slingshot to launch angry birds to destroy pigs and their fortresses.
Photo






Walter Isaacson

Credit
            Andreas Solaro/Agence France-Presse ‚Äî Getty Images        


So ‚ÄúSteve Jobs,‚Äù an account of its subject‚Äôs 56 years (he died on Oct. 5), must reach across time in more ways than one. And it does, in a well-ordered, if not streamlined, fashion. It begins with a portrait of the young Mr. Jobs, rebellious toward the parents who raised him and scornful of the ones who gave him up for adoption. (‚ÄúThey were my sperm and egg bank,‚Äù he says.)Although Mr. Isaacson is not analytical about his subject‚Äôs volatile personality (the word ‚Äúobnoxious‚Äù figures in the book frequently), he raises the question of whether feelings of abandonment in childhood made him fanatically controlling and manipulative as an adult. Fortunately, that glib question stays unanswered.Mr. Jobs, who founded Apple with Stephen Wozniak and Ronald Wayne in 1976, began his career as a seemingly contradictory blend of hippie truth seeker and tech-savvy hothead.
Photo






Cover of the book "Steve Jobs" by Walter Isaacson.

Credit
            Alessandra Montalto/The New York Times        


‚ÄúHis Zen awareness was not accompanied by an excess of calm, peace of mind or interpersonal mellowness,‚Äù Mr. Isaacson says. ‚ÄúHe could stun an unsuspecting victim with an emotional towel-snap, perfectly aimed,‚Äù he also writes. But Mr. Jobs valued simplicity, utility and beauty in ways that would shape his creative imagination. And the book maintains that those goals would not have been achievable in the great parade of Apple creations without that mean streak.Mr. Isaacson takes his readers back to the time when laptops, desktops and windows were metaphors, not everyday realities. His book ticks off how each of the Apple innovations that we now take for granted first occurred to Mr. Jobs or his creative team. ‚ÄúSteve Jobs‚Äù means to be the authoritative book about those achievements, and it also follows Mr. Jobs into the wilderness (and to NeXT and Pixar) after his first stint at Apple, which ended in 1985.With an avid interest in corporate intrigue, it skewers Mr. Jobs‚Äôs rivals, like John Sculley, who was recruited in 1983 to be Apple‚Äôs chief executive and fell for Mr. Jobs‚Äôs deceptive show of friendship. ‚ÄúThey professed their fondness so effusively and often that they sounded like high school sweethearts at a Hallmark card display,‚Äù Mr. Isaacson writes.
Photo






Steve Jobs introduced the new Macintosh personal computer on Jan. 24, 1984.

Credit
            Paul Sakuma/Associated Press        


Of course the book also tracks Mr. Jobs‚Äôs long and combative rivalry with Bill Gates. The section devoted to Mr. Jobs‚Äôs illness, which suggests that his cancer might have been more treatable had he not resisted early surgery, describes the relative tenderness of their last meeting.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

‚ÄúSteve Jobs‚Äù greatly admires its subject. But its most adulatory passages are not about people. Offering a combination of tech criticism and promotional hype, Mr. Isaacson describes the arrival of each new product right down to Mr. Jobs‚Äôs theatrical introductions and the advertising campaigns. But if the individual bits of hoopla seem excessive, their cumulative effect is staggering. Here is an encyclopedic survey of all that Mr. Jobs accomplished, replete with the passion and excitement that it deserves.Mr. Jobs‚Äôs virtual reinvention of the music business with iTunes and the iPod, for instance, is made to seem all the more miraculous (‚ÄúHe‚Äôs got a turn-key solution,‚Äù the music executive Jimmy Iovine said.) Mr. Isaacson‚Äôs long view basically puts Mr. Jobs up there with Franklin and Einstein, even if a tiny MP3 player is not quite the theory of relativity. The book emphasizes how deceptively effortless Mr. Jobs‚Äôs ideas now seem because of their extreme intuitiveness and foresight. When Mr. Jobs, who personally persuaded musician after musician to accept the iTunes model, approached Wynton Marsalis, Mr. Marsalis was rightly more impressed with Mr. Jobs than with the device he was being shown.
