Mr. Jobs‚Äôs love of music plays a big role in ‚ÄúSteve Jobs,‚Äù like his extreme obsession with Bob Dylan. (Like Mr. Dylan, he had a romance with Joan Baez. Her version of Mr. Dylan‚Äôs ‚ÄúLove Is Just a Four-Letter Word‚Äù was on Mr. Jobs‚Äôs own iPod.) So does his extraordinary way of perceiving ordinary things, like well-made knives and kitchen appliances. That he admired the Cuisinart food processor he saw at Macy‚Äôs may sound trivial, but his subsequent idea that a molded plastic covering might work well on a computer does not. Years from now, the research trip to a jelly bean factory to study potential colors for the iMac case will not seem as silly as it might now.Skeptic after skeptic made the mistake of underrating Steve Jobs, and Mr. Isaacson records the howlers who misjudged an unrivaled career. ‚ÄúSorry Steve, Here‚Äôs Why Apple Stores Won‚Äôt Work,‚Äù Business Week wrote in a 2001 headline. ‚ÄúThe iPod will likely become a niche product,‚Äù a Harvard Business School professor said. ‚ÄúHigh tech could not be designed and sold as a consumer product,‚Äù Mr. Sculley said in 1987.Mr. Jobs got the last laugh every time. ‚ÄúSteve Jobs‚Äù makes it all the sadder that his last laugh is over.

STEVE JOBS


By Walter Isaacson

 Illustrated. 630 pages. Simon & Schuster. $35.


 Correction: October 26, 2011  
The Books of The Times review on Saturday, about ‚ÄúSteve Jobs,‚Äù by Walter Isaacson, described Angry Birds, a popular iPhone game, incorrectly. Slingshots are used to launch birds to destroy pigs and their fortresses, not to shoot down the birds. 


Continue reading the main story






